Yes, we&#39;re using junit with WebObjects. I posted a message to the WebObjects
list about it a little while ago, (below). I&#39;ve since upgraded to junit 3.5
and the line which starts the test runner has changed to:

new junit.awtui.TestRunner().start(new String[]{&quot;AllTests&quot;});

Another thing I forgot to mention in the post below is that I&#39;ve added a
static inner class to my Application which provides access to Application
from within your TestCase. The inner class is constructed with a live
application in the Application constructor.

    /**
     * provides static access to the application instance for the unit
tests.
     */
    public static class Access {

        private static Access instance;
        private Application app;

        private Access(Application app) {
            this.app = app;
        }

        public static Access instance() {
            return instance;
        }

        public Application application() {
            return app;
        }

    }

Then in your test case you just write
Application.Access.instance().application() to get hold of the reference.
From there you can call pageWithName() or whatever to get hold of pages, a
Session etc.

I havn&#39;t yet got this working in a deployment environment, but it&#39;s been
very useful in my development environment.

Hope that helps,

Emily

----- posted to &#39;webobjects-dev@...&#39; on Mon 5th Feb -------

I have started to introduce unit testing to an existing WO application. I
have used JUnit on previous pure Java projects and I know how valuable it is
to have them. One of the problems I found running JUnit with WO is that your
WOComponents etc need to be instantiated with suitably initialised
Application and Session objects, so I found I needed to kick the tests off
from within the running application, instead of kicking off the tests and
having them instantiate the application. Therefore I&#39;ve put this bit of code
in the constructor of my Main class, which is called after the application
is properly started up and is ready to go:

	public Main() {
        app = (Application) application();
        s = (Session) session();

        if (app.shouldRunTests() && !app.testsRunningNow()) {
            app.setTestsRunningNow(true);

            // run the tests in their own thread
            Runnable runnable = new Runnable(){
                public void run() {
                    new junit.ui.TestRunner().start(new
String[]{&quot;AllTests&quot;}, new junit.util.StandardTestSuiteLoader());
                }
            };
            Thread testThread = new java.lang.Thread(runnable);
            testThread.start();
        }
    }

The unit tests run in their own thread, but my application wasn&#39;t designed
for multithreading, so I usually wait until all my unit tests have finished
before trying to access the application manually. The other thing is that if
you click &quot;exit&quot; on the unit test window, your whole application exits - I
havn&#39;t found a way round this yet. Also note that my tests have to be really
careful to leave my Application class in the same state it found it. (It&#39;s
fairly easy to set it up so that every test gets its own session).

As for functional, (black box, user perspective) tests, I tried WOUnit,
http://wounit.jmltech.com/ (I just tried the site and it&#39;s down - anyone
know what happened to it?) which is based on httpUnit. I found it to be more
designed for static sites, and wasn&#39;t actually giving me much once I needed
to log in and keep track of my session state, so I just used plain httpUnit.
This was working well until I ran into a brick wall: javascript and
VBScript. My pages are absolutely littered with the stuff, and httpUnit
doesn&#39;t have any kind of scripting interpreter and can&#39;t imitate a browser
in that way. I had to put creation of automated functional tests on hold
basically, until either httpUnit adds support for scripting or we manage to
refactor out the scripting from our pages.

I&#39;d be very interested to hear how other WO developers have been using JUnit
or other unit testing frameworks, or if you have criticisms of my approach.

Regards,
Emily

